<Procedure id="_i" name="getInstanceId">
<comment>This procedure returns an ID.

QF-Test recognizes the Runid as an ID that can be used as an instance ID.

Alternatively, an external program can pass a value via a global variable, which can then be interpreted as an instance ID.

@return    The procedure returns an instance ID.</comment>
<ServerScriptStep id="_j" interpreter="groovy" name="script_common-environment-getInstanceId">
<code>if(!rc.getGlobals().containsKey("INSTANCEID"))
{
  rc.setLocal("getInstanceId", rc.getStr("qftest","runid"))
}
else
{
  rc.setLocal("getInstanceId", rc.getStr("INSTANCEID"))
}</code>
</ServerScriptStep>
<ReturnStep id="_k" retval="$(getInstanceId)"/>
</Procedure>
</Package>
</Package>
<Package id="_C" name="neoload">
<Package id="_3Vl" name="recording">
<comment>The scripts in load testing are generally based on pure network traffic, whereas QF-Test typically interacts with the SUT via the GUI.

With the RecordingListener, a test case can be played back with QF-Test and recorded with NeoLoad. The recording must then be edited by a tester, as dynamic content must be replaced using variables.

The low-level test case to be recorded only needs to be adjusted in terms of browser instantiation so that network traffic runs through the NeoLoad proxy. </comment>
<Procedure id="_3Vm" name="addRecordingListener">
<variable name="strNeoloadController">${as:string:localhost}</variable>
<variable name="iPort">${as:integer:7400}</variable>
<variable name="strAPIKey">${as:string:${default:NEOLOADAPIKEY:}}</variable>
<variable name="strNeoloadProjectMode">${as:string:CURRENT}</variable>
<variable name="strNeoloadProjectPath">${as:string:}</variable>
<variable name="strNeoloadProjectName">${as:string:}</variable>
<variable name="bProtocolWebSocket">${as:boolean:true}</variable>
<variable name="bProtocolAdobeRTMP">${as:boolean:false}</variable>
<variable name="bProtocolHTTP2">${as:boolean:true}</variable>
<comment>This procedure instantiates the RecordingListener and registers it with the QF-Test engine.

The RecordingListener takes control of NeoLoad while one or more test cases are executed in QF-Test. 

Since network traffic must be recorded via a proxy, it is assumed that at any given time, only one instance of the listener should be registered. If the procedure is called multiple times in succession, the current instance is always terminated first, and a new instance is registered.

@param	strNeoloadController	This parameter should be set to the host on 
			which the NeoLoad Controller is running. 
			It is recommended that NeoLoad and QF-Test be 
			run on the same machine; in this case, the 
			default value &#8220;localhost&#8221; can be used.
@param	iPort		This parameter specifies the port through which 
			the NeoLoad Controller can be accessed. If the port 
			has not been changed in the NeoLoad configuration, 
			it is generally port 7400, which is set as the 
			default value.
@param	strAPIKey		To secure communication with NeoLoad interfaces, 
			an API key can be stored in NeoLoad. If this is 
			the case, the API key must be provided in this 
			parameter so that QF-Test can communicate with 
			NeoLoad. 
			Otherwise, the parameter can be left blank.
@param	strNeoloadProjectMode	This parameter specifies where the recording should be saved.
			The default value is &#8220;CURRENT,&#8221; which assumes that the 
			recording should be saved in the currently open project. 
			If &#8216;CREATE&#8217; is specified, a project is created with the name 
			specified in the strNeoloadProjectName parameter. 
			If the project already exists, it will be overwritten. 
			If &#8220;OPEN&#8221; is specified, the project passed via the 
			strNeoloadProjectPath parameter will be opened before 
			recording begins.
@param	strNeoloadProjectPath	If the caller wants a project to be opened, the full path to 
			the NeoLoad project file must be passed in this parameter.
@param	strNeoloadProjectName	In this parameter, you must specify the name of the project 
			that NeoLoad should create before recording.
@param	bProtocolWebSocket	This option makes it possible to record a WebSocket application.
@param	bProtocolAdobeRTMP	This option allows you to record an Adobe RTMP application. 
			Before setting this switch to true, you should carefully read 
			the NeoLoad documentation.
@param	bProtocolHTTP2	This switch allows you to specify whether NeoLoad should 
			support HTTP/2.0 applications during recording. If you are not 
			familiar with this feature, we recommend leaving the switch 
			set to true.

@author	Dirk O. Schweier</comment>
<ServerScriptStep id="_3Vn" interpreter="groovy" name="script_neoload_recording_addRecordingListener">
